         <abstract>
            <p>Let α be an algebraic integer of degree d, not 0 or a root of unity, all of whose conjugates α&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt; are confined to a sector &lt;tex-math&gt;$|\arg z| \leq \theta$&lt;/tex-math&gt;. We compute the greatest lower bound c(θ) of the absolute Mahler measure &lt;tex-math&gt;$(\prod^d_{i = 1} \max(1,|\alpha_i|))^{1/d}$&lt;/tex-math&gt; of α, for θ belonging to nine subintervals of [ 0, 2π/3]. In particular, we show that c(π/2) = 1.12933793, from which it follows that any integer α ≠ 1 and α ≠ e&lt;sup&gt;± iπ/3&lt;/sup&gt; all of whose conjugates have positive real part has absolute Mahler measure at least c(π/2). This value is achieved for α satisfying α + 1/α = β&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt;, where β&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; = 1.3247 ... is the smallest Pisot number (the real root of β&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; = β&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; + 1).</p>
          </abstract>
